// ── ENC DATA ──
const encData={
  nvy:{title:'Nagar Van Yojana (NVY)',body:`<p>The Nagar Van Yojana (NVY) is India's flagship urban forestry scheme launched by the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change (MoEFCC) under the National Afforestation and Eco-Development Board (NAEB). It targets the development of 1000 urban forests across Indian cities by 2027.</p><p>The scheme provides financial support ranging from ₹50 lakh to ₹2 crore per city per year, channeled through CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority). Eligible cities must have a population exceeding 1 lakh and are expected to identify suitable land parcels — typically degraded municipal or revenue land — for forest development.</p><p>Critically, NVY's current PMU (Programme Management Unit) reporting framework relies predominantly on quantitative indicators: number of saplings planted, survival rates, area covered, and NDVI change. This creates a measurement gap that obscures human-centric outcomes including well-being, livelihood impact, and community participation.</p><p><strong style="color:var(--accent)">Key evaluation gaps:</strong> No standardized well-being measurement protocol exists. Livelihood co-benefits are untracked. Community governance structures remain informal. The welfare-to-rights paradigm shift remains unrealized at the implementation level.</p>`},
  campa:{title:'CAMPA & CAF Act 2016',body:`<p>The Compensatory Afforestation Fund (CAF) Act 2016 established a legal framework for managing compensatory afforestation funds collected from project proponents whose activities divert forest land. The Act created a pooled corpus estimated at over ₹66,000 crore — one of India's largest environmental funds.</p><p>National CAMPA (under MoEFCC) provides policy direction and oversight, while 36 State CAMPAs manage actual implementation. Annual Plans of Operations (APOs) govern fund disbursement for ecological restoration, urban forestry, wildlife protection, and biodiversity conservation.</p><p>The NVY draws significantly from CAMPA allocations, creating a critical link between industrial forest diversion and urban green infrastructure investment — a compensatory logic that remains under-examined in policy literature.</p>`},
  ndvi:{title:'NDVI & Urban Green Space Monitoring',body:`<p>The Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) is calculated from near-infrared (NIR) and red spectral bands of satellite imagery using the formula: NDVI = (NIR − Red) / (NIR + Red). Values range from -1 to +1, where values above 0.3 typically indicate healthy vegetation.</p><p>For NVY monitoring, NDVI analysis is conducted through the e-Green Watch platform and cross-referenced with KML boundary files of individual forest patches. Sentinel-2 (10m resolution) and Landsat-8 (30m) are the primary satellite sources used in Indian urban forestry monitoring.</p><p>However, NDVI has limitations in urban contexts: it cannot distinguish between native biodiversity-rich plantations and monoculture lawns, both of which may show similar NDVI values. It also fails to capture understory diversity, soil health, or community access equity — all critical outcomes for a human-centric NVY evaluation.</p>`},
  uhi:{title:'Urban Heat Island (UHI) Effect',body:`<p>The Urban Heat Island (UHI) effect occurs when built urban surfaces (concrete, asphalt, glass) absorb and re-emit solar radiation more intensely than natural vegetation, causing urban temperatures to exceed surrounding rural areas by 2–5°C or more — up to 10°C in extreme cases.</p><p>Urban forests mitigate UHI through three primary mechanisms: (1) Evapotranspiration — trees release water vapor, cooling surrounding air; (2) Shading — canopy cover reduces solar radiation reaching surfaces; (3) Albedo modification — vegetated surfaces reflect more solar energy than dark built surfaces.</p><p>Studies indicate that well-established urban forests can reduce local surface temperatures by 5–8°C. In Indian cities facing extreme heat events (Surat, Ahmedabad, Nagpur), this cooling effect translates to measurable public health outcomes including reduced heat-related mortality and hospital admissions.</p><p>The PRANA portal (Programme for National Air Quality) tracks co-benefits of urban green infrastructure including particulate matter (PM2.5/PM10) reduction — closely linked to tree cover in Indian urban areas.</p>`},
  cvm:{title:'Contingent Valuation Method (CVM)',body:`<p>The Contingent Valuation Method (CVM) is a stated preference technique used in environmental economics to estimate the monetary value that people assign to non-market environmental goods — such as clean air, biodiversity, or urban forest ecosystem services.</p><p>In the NVY evaluation framework, CVM is applied using a double-bounded dichotomous choice (DBDC) design, where respondents are first asked whether they would be willing to pay (WTP) a certain amount (Bid A), then followed up with a higher (Bid B+) or lower bid (Bid B-) depending on their initial response. This design is statistically more efficient than single-bounded formats and yields tighter confidence intervals around WTP estimates.</p><p>For NVY sites in Surat and Gandhinagar, the CVM instrument presents a hypothetical scenario: respondents are asked about their WTP for improved urban forest access, maintenance, and expansion — controlling for income, distance to site, frequency of use, and socioeconomic characteristics.</p><p>The resulting WTP estimates are aggregated across urban populations to derive a total economic value of NVY ecosystem services per site — a figure that strengthens the policy case for CAMPA investment in urban forestry beyond ecological rationale alone.</p>`},
  slf:{title:'Sustainable Livelihoods Framework (SLF)',body:`<p>The Sustainable Livelihoods Framework (SLF), developed by DFID and adapted for diverse research contexts, conceptualizes household vulnerability and resilience through five capital asset categories: Human Capital (skills, health, education), Social Capital (networks, trust, institutions), Natural Capital (land, water, forests), Physical Capital (infrastructure, tools), and Financial Capital (savings, income, credit access).</p><p>In the NVY evaluation, SLF provides a holistic lens for assessing how urban forest development affects the livelihood profiles of communities living adjacent to NVY sites. A pentagon radar diagram visualizes the relative strength of each capital for different demographic subgroups — allowing comparison between pre- and post-NVY scenarios.</p><p>Key research questions addressed by SLF in the Gujarat fieldwork include: Does NVY access improve natural capital (recreational use, herbs, shade)? Does it build social capital (community governance, participation)? Does it affect human capital (mental health, physical activity)? The SLF answers these through FGDs, social mapping, and structured KII interviews with ULB officials and forest department staff.</p>`},
