// ── ARTICLE EXPAND ──
function openArticle(){
  document.getElementById('enc-expand-content').innerHTML=`
    <h2>India's Urban Heat Crisis: From Welfare to Rights</h2>
    <p><em>April 2026 · Arkraj Biswas · National CAMPA / GRAAM Embark Fellowship</em></p>
    <p>India's cities are heating up — literally. As urban heat islands intensify across Surat, Indore, Ranchi, and Visakhapatnam, the Nagar Van Yojana (NVY) emerges not merely as an afforestation scheme, but as a critical mechanism in a deeper paradigm shift: from viewing urban forests as welfare amenities to recognizing green space access as a fundamental environmental right.</p>
    <p>This essay interrogates the tension between NVY's quantitative reporting logic — tree counts, survival rates, NDVI indices — and the more complex, contested terrain of distributive justice in urban green space. Who benefits from a city forest? Which communities bear the land acquisition cost? How does spatial proximity to an NVY site correlate with socioeconomic status?</p>
    <p>Across four cities visited during this fellowship year, a consistent pattern emerges: NVY forests are disproportionately located on land that is geographically accessible to middle and upper-income localities, while peri-urban and informal settlement communities — often the most exposed to urban heat — remain underserved by the scheme's current spatial planning logic.</p>
    <p>The welfare-to-rights paradigm demands we reframe the question: not merely "How many trees were planted?" but "Whose well-being improved? Who gained livelihood stability? Who was included in the governance of this public good?"</p>
